Rahgot's sarcophagus (OPEN): What they see: A massive stone sarcophagus, lid shoved aside, interior empty. Ward-runes dark. A body-impression in the dust. If they investigate (Magic TN 12): The ward-runes were a death-sleep preservation system ΓÇö keeping the occupant in suspended animation for millennia. They were deactivated deliberately, from the inside. Whatever was in here woke up on its own and walked out. The dust impression shows a large humanoid form wearing a mask. The sarcophagus carvings identify the occupant: Rahgot, Dragon Priest of the Last Redoubt.
If they investigate further (Magic TN 14; or Alfonso's domain if his player claims it, no roll): The carvings around the sarcophagus tell a story. Dragon Priests were the mortal servants of the dragons during the Merethic Era ΓÇö men and women who ruled over human kingdoms as intermediaries between the dragon gods and their mortal subjects. They were granted immense power and near-immortality in exchange for absolute devotion. When the ancient Nords overthrew the Dragon Cult in the Dragon War, most priests were killed or sealed in their tombs in death-sleep.
The carvings name FIVE priests who entered death-sleep rather than face destruction. Each has a title and a mask:
Nahkriin the Guardian ΓÇö mask of vengeance. Spymaster. Guards the path to Sovngarde.
Vokun the Shadow ΓÇö mask of shadow. Tactician and siege commander.
Rahgot the Angry ΓÇö mask of fury. Alchemist-priest. Weapon of environmental destruction. This sarcophagus.
Otar the Mad ΓÇö mask of madness. A king who believes his kingdom never fell.
Morokei the Glorious ΓÇö mask of glory. Archmage. The most powerful of the five.
The carvings depict a final image: all five masks placed together on a single altar, forming a sixth mask ΓÇö Konahrik, the Warlord. The inscription beneath reads: "When the World-Eater returns, the faithful shall rise. When the five become one, the faithful shall ascend."
What this means: The Dragon Priests aren't just waking up to serve Alduin. They have their own agenda. The five masks combine into something greater. "Ascend" implies apotheosis ΓÇö they intend to become gods. Alduin is their vehicle, not their master.
FOR THE GM (Alfonso's domain -- offer it, don't speak it for him): the carvings place Rahgot as an alchemist-priest whose doctrine four thousand years ago was environmental warfare. That makes Antoine his successor rather than his inventor: Rahgot woke, found a chemist already at work in his laboratory, and put him to use. The plagues are Rahgot's; Antoine is the instrument. If Alfonso's player reaches this, let him land it.
Why planted here: The empty sarcophagus is the session's biggest revelation. Dragon Priests are awake, active, organized, and pursuing apotheosis. Rahgot specifically is loose in the world with an alchemist-servant and a grudge against the descendants who besieged his fortress. This connects directly to the Dragon Cult clock's Tier 3 event (Rahgot's ecological assault on the Rift).
The Strain 2.0 design folder: What they see: Antoine's active research on the next-generation pathogen. If they investigate: See detailed breakdown below. Why planted here: The primary intelligence reward and the party's ticking clock.
The culture dishes: What they see: Sealed glass dishes arranged in grids. If they investigate: Active pathogen cultures in various stages. This is where the infection risk lives. If containment was breached (Outcomes B or C), these are now open to the air. If containment held (Outcome A), they're still sealed and safe to study. Why planted here: The source of the infection and also a potential loot item ΓÇö sealed culture samples are worth 500g each to Maven (proof of the operation) or to Alfonso (research material).
