A. THE HIDDEN ANCIENT JOURNAL  (Section 3, current room -- THE fresh find of the session)
-----------------------------------------------------------------
The thing in the journals room the party has NOT seen. A thin, water-swollen old volume is
wedged under the short leg of Antoine's main workbench, leveling it. He keeps it where his
boot can reach and his eyes need not go -- the oldest private journal in Forelhost, and the
one book here its master will not open. A player who looks under the bench, or rocks the
unsteady table, finds it.
THE TEXT (a Keeper many generations back; plain log voice):
  "Forty-one years tending the fire. I have buried my father and my wife and a son who did
   not see his second winter, and I have kept the cauldron at heat through all of it.
   I will set down the thing we keep out of the open ledgers, because I am old and the boy
   is not yet old enough to be ruined by it.
   I have never heard the god. Not in the smoke, not in the dark, not over my wife's grave
   when I begged Him for one word. My father never heard Him. His father wrote the same, in
   the book beneath this one, in a hand I can barely read.
   The first of us stayed because he watched four thousand people drink and lie down, and he
   held his own cup in his own hand, and his hand would not lift it. He called it duty by
   morning. We have called it duty for four thousand years. It is the longest a family has
   ever been afraid in one place.
   I keep the fire for the boy, so the work will mean something when I put it in his hands.
   That is the whole of my faith and I will pretend to no more than that."
WHAT THIS ESTABLISHES (GM-only): the founding was inherited fear dressed as duty -- and the
  family's oldest secret is that NONE of them ever heard their god. This is the hinge the
  dungeon swings on, and it makes Antoine's own crack (drop C) hereditary: he stands on this
  book every day and will not read it. Hand the players the journal; let them open it.
  (If the GM wants the doubt to run deeper, "the book beneath this one" can become a second
  find -- an older Keeper saying the same in a rougher hand.)

